<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-657-177  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 657 177.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Nov 26 1990 v24 n48 p92(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>More firms taking road to PC rentals to meet demands.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Claiborne, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>More and more companies are choosing to rent rather than buycomputers in order to meet the demands of workers who requireequipment for a temporary period.andP;  Rentals can be the mostcost-effective solution when a company is under pressure tofulfill a government or other contract.andP;  A company that chooses torent is spared most maintenance and depreciation costs, and mostrental contracts specify that the rental agent is responsible forall maintenance over the contract period.andP;  Renting costs more thanbuying for meeting long-term needs but is ideal for short-termneeds.andP;  Many potential computer renters are not aware of thenumber of companies that can supply equipment by the day, week ormonth.andP;  Computerland Corp and Businessland Inc, two major retailchains, have rental outlets; other companies are entering therental business through franchising.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MicrocomputersRentingLeasingEquipment AcquisitionManagement of EDP.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>